def: Having many names or titles; polyonymous. Sir W. Jones.
One of a tribe of beetles (Malacodermata), with a soft andflexible body, as the fireflies.
The state or quality of being irreducible.
To bite; to gnaw. [Written also roin.] [Obs.] Spenser.

In Old English, the article the, when the following word beganwith a vowel, was often written with elision as if a part of theword. Thus in Chaucer, the forms thabsence, tharray, thegle, thend,thingot, etc., are found for the absence, the array, the eagle, theend, etc.
Of or pertaining to the pulse.
Formerly, a soldier who was taught and armed to serve either onhorseback or on foot; now, a mounted soldier; a cavalry man.
Learned. [Obs.] " Lewed man or lered." Chaucer.
A combining form denoting form, shape; as, isomorphous.
In the form of an hyperbola.
